\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Engineer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A train engineer is the task that calculates immediete information regarding
 the train.
 It is a server which receives from the UIWorker, engineerCourier, and the
 parser.
 Associated with the Engineer are data such as: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Position
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Speed (from 0 to 14)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Velocity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Last hit sensors and time pair
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Upon starting the engineer it drives until it hits a sensor.
 This tells it where it is and it updates its landmarks.
 When it receives a sensor update, or an location update from the UI worker,
 it recalculates its current landmark.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It also keeps track of which sensor will be hit next and when.
 There is a table that stores timing between sensor reads.
 The table is updated in a feedback loop fashion for accurate train velocity
 estimation 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}=(1-\alpha)v_{0}+\alpha v'$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is the learning rate.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=85\%$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sensor Update
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The engineer task is notified of sensor update via the engineerCourier,
 with the other end being the sensorServer.
 The engineerCourier first calls Send() to the sensorServer, and when the
 sensor server receives an update, the engineerCourier is replied with the
 sensor ID and a timestamp.
 The courier then call Send() to the engineer task.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a sensor update is delivered to the engineer, the engineer knows that
 a sensor has been triggered.
 The sensor updates the sensor-time table that stores time between pairs
 of sensors, updates the previous landmark, next landmark, distance to next
 landmark, previous sensor (which is the sensor in this sensor update),
 current velocity (length of segment between two sensors / time since last
 sensor ), expected time (which is computed from the time of previous sensor
 update plus the value in the sensor-time table), the actual time (which
 is the timestamp of the sensor update), and error (abs(actual time - expected
 time)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Display Of Location Information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The display of location information is managed by both the engineer and
 the UIWorker.
 The UIWorker is a worker task that Send() an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

update_location
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 request to the engineer every 5 ticks.
 After the engineer process the request, it is replied with updates to the
 screen.
 It then prints out the replied data to COM2 via a printf() call, and then
 calls Send() to the engineer again.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On receiving an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

update_location
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 request, the engineer computes how far it's gone over previous landmark,
 then computes the next landmark.
 If the next landmark is a sensor, then the engineer replies to the UIWorker
 with the distance to the next sensor.
 If the next landmark is not a sensor, then the engineer get the distance
 from previous landmark to next landmark from the track graph; it checks
 to see if the distance that the train has gone past the previous landmark
 is greater or equal to that distance.
 If it is, then we assume that we've reached the next landmark and output
 all of the related information; else, only the distance to the next landmark
 is printed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
X Marks The Spot
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the train has to be able to stop at arbitrarily far from a sensor position,
 the engineer spawns 2 helper tasks.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
One task that delays for a certain duration then replies to the engineer.
 This is used so the engineer can update its landmark references after certain
 time has passed and it should be at a new landmark.
 The engineer wakes up, replies to the timer task, prints to the screen
 and sleeps again.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
One task that shuffles sensor updates from the sensor task to engineer,
 to update the engineer of a sensor reading.
 As it keeps moving, the model of its speed is corrected in a feedback loop
 fashion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The stopping distance is derived from the current calculated speed.
 When the position is exactly the stopping distance ahead of it, it starts
 decelerating, to stop (at its best estimate) on X.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no reverse.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Path Finding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pathing is not implemented.
 But in the future, when the engineer sent an instruction to navigate to
 another position, it calculate a path using Djikstra's algorithm, and avoid
 revisiting the same nodes over and over.
 Exit nodes would have a distance of infinity to make the path avoid using
 it.
 After planning, the engineer requests ownership of the track it needs before
 it starts moving forward.
 As it moves, it sets the turnouts (which it owns) that are at most its
 stopping distance along its path.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sensors Calibration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We drive the train, and give it a stop command when it hits a desired sensor
 (set via our command) so that the pickup is right at the sensor.
 Then measure the distance that it takes the train to stop, and calculate
 the deceleration.
 This number is used for stopping at a desired node by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

looking ahead
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by such distance to check if it is the desired node.
\end_layout

